There is a couple of other weird thing about the JUnit taskdef. 

a.) JUnit is included as part of the optional.jar from ant which is in
my $ANT_HOME/lib directory, yet I still have to provide the following
statement to get it to see the Junit Taskdef.

&lt;taskdef name=&quot;junit&quot;
classname=&quot;org.apache.tools.ant.taskdefs.optional.junit.JUnitTask&quot; /&gt;

Maybe I misunderstood this, but I thought that taskdefs defined in the
optional jar did not need to be explicitly defined.

b.) Why is JUnit the only taskdef that I am having this problem with. 


--- In junit@y..., Vitezslav Stejskal &lt;vitezslav.stejskal@c...&gt; wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; There is a several things you have to keep in
&gt; mind when using Ant:
&gt; 
&gt; * all tasks are instantiated during the parsing time, even if they
will
&gt; never be launched
&gt; 
&gt; * tasks are loaded using the system classpath or the classpath
&gt; defined in the taskdef element, this allows you to load
&gt; task&#39;s class from the classpath defined in your script
&gt; 
&gt; * the above rule has an exception - tasks placed in the
&gt; package org.apache.tools.ant are *always* loaded using
&gt; the system classpath
&gt; 
&gt; Thus all built-in and optional tasks are loaded from the system
&gt; classpath as well as any other class they need (in your case the
junit
&gt; classes).
&gt; 
&gt; So far I see two options:
&gt; * put junit.jar on the system&#39;s claspath
&gt; (modify CLASSPATH environment variable or put it into the
&gt; ${ANT_HOME}/lib directory)
&gt; 
&gt; * create new class derived from the
org.apache.tools.ant.taskdef.optional.junit.JUnitTask,
&gt; place it in your own package and use the taskdef element to redefine
Ant&#39;s default
&gt; junit task.
&gt; 
&gt; Vita
&gt; 
